Active Planned Care / GoalsStart DateReason
Dementia management19-Jul-2022Alzheimer's disease (disorder)
  • Support maintenance of current cognitive abilities and slow progression of cognitive decline.
  • Enable patient to perform basic activities of daily living (ADLs) with minimal assistance.
  • Minimize frequency and severity of behavioral disturbances such as agitation, aggression, or wandering.
  • Ensure patient or caregiver administers prescribed dementia medications as directed.
  • Ensure caregiver receives education and support to manage dementia-related care needs.
Discharge care plan08-Nov-2007History of aortic valve replacement (situation)
  • Patient and caregiver will demonstrate understanding of discharge instructions, including medication regimen, activity restrictions, and follow-up appointments.
  • All medications will be reviewed and reconciled to ensure accuracy and safety at discharge.
  • Discharge instructions will be communicated using strategies appropriate for cognitive impairment, with caregiver involvement.
  • Hemoglobin level will be maintained within the target range prior to discharge.
  • Fasting glucose will be maintained within the prediabetes range prior to discharge.
  • Patient will be hemodynamically stable with no new or worsening symptoms of ischemic heart disease or aortic valve dysfunction at discharge.
Care plan04-Oct-2007Aortic valve stenosis (disorder)
  • Minimize dyspnea, fatigue, and chest pain related to aortic valve stenosis
  • Maintain systolic blood pressure below 140 mmHg
  • Maintain hemoglobin above 11 g/dL
  • Monitor B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP) to detect worsening heart failure
Diabetes self management plan13-Jan-1981Prediabetes
  • Maintain hemoglobin A1c (HbA1c) below 6.5% to reduce risk of progression to diabetes.
  • Achieve and maintain a healthy body weight to support glycemic control.
  • Engage in at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity physical activity per week as tolerated.
  • Adopt a balanced diet with reduced intake of simple sugars and saturated fats to support glycemic control.
  • Maintain blood pressure below 130/80 mmHg to reduce cardiovascular risk.
